  "local_port": 40720,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What should I do if I lost my Chase debit card?",
  "response": "If you\u2019ve lost your Chase debit card, it\u2019s important to act quickly to protect your account and finances. Here\u2019s what you should do:\n\n### 1. **Lock or Report Your Card Lost or Stolen**\n   - **Through the Chase Mobile App**:\n     1. Log in to the Chase Mobile App.\n     2. Go to the account linked to the lost debit card.\n     3. Tap on \u201cShow details\u201d or \u201cManage Card.\u201d\n     4. Select \u201cLock & Unlock\u201d to temporarily lock the card or \u201cReport Lost or Stolen\u201d to permanently deactivate it.\n   - **Online Banking**:\n     1. Log in to your Chase account online.\n     2. Navigate to the account associated with the debit card.\n     3. Click on \u201cMore\u201d or \u201cAccount Services\u201d and select \u201cLock & Unlock\u201d or \u201cReport Lost or Stolen.\u201d\n   - **By Phone**:\n     Call Chase customer service at **1-800-935-9935** (available 24/7) to report the card lost or stolen.\n\n### 2. **Monitor Your Account for Fraudulent Activity**\n   - Check your recent transactions online or through the app to ensure no unauthorized purchases were made.\n   - If you notice any suspicious activity, report it to Chase immediately.\n\n### 3. **Request a Replacement Card**\n   - When reporting your card lost or stolen, you can request a replacement card. It typically arrives within **3\u20135 business days**.\n   - You may have the option to expedite the delivery of your replacement card for a fee.\n\n### 4. **Update Automatic Payments**\n   - If you\u2019ve linked your lost debit card to any subscriptions or automatic payments, update them with your new card details once you receive the replacement.\n\n### 5. **Stay Vigilant**\n   - Keep an eye on your account and credit report for signs of identity theft.\n   - Consider enabling account alerts through Chase to monitor transactions in real time.\n\n### 6. **Check for Account Compromise**\n   - If you suspect your account may have been compromised, consider changing your online banking password and PIN for added security.\n\nIf you have any questions or need assistance, Chase customer service is available to help.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
